[[Image:Scrub Island (Anguilla).jpg|thumb|right|View of Scrub Bay]] [[File:Anguilla-CIA WFB Map (2004).png|thumb|right|Map of Anguilla; Scrub Island lies off the north-eastern tip of the main island]]
'''Scrub Island''' is an {{convert|8|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} island lying off the eastern tip of the main island of [[Anguilla]], a [[British Overseas Territory]] in the [[Caribbean]]. It is easily reached by boat. Privately owned, the remains of an abandoned air field still exist. There are several abandoned houses on the island, mainly due to damage from hurricanes. There is no electricity or plumbing.
==Fauna== The island has been identified as an [[Important Bird Area]] by [[BirdLife International]], mainly because of its nesting [[seabird]]s. These are [[laughing gull]]s as well as [[royal tern|royal]], [[roseate tern|roseate]] and [[least tern]]s. Resident landbirds include [[Caribbean elaenia]]s and [[pearly-eyed thrasher]]s. The island's five species of reptiles comprise the [[Anguilla Bank ameiva]], ''[[Anguilla Bank anole|Anolis gingivinus]]'', [[Sphaerodactylus parvus|little dwarf gecko]], [[Sphaerodactylus sputator|island dwarf gecko]] and the [[endangered species|endangered]] [[leeward island racer]]. [[Green turtle|Green]] and [[leatherback turtle]]s have been recorded. [[Feral goat]]s and [[rat]]s are present.<ref name=bli>{{cite web |url= http://www.birdlife.org |title= Scrub Island|accessdate=2012-11-23 |work= BirdLife data zone: Important Bird Areas |first= |last= |publisher= BirdLife International |date= 2012}}</ref> [[Whale]]s are commonly seen west of Scrub, along the southern coastline.
